xxl.core.indexStructures.builder.BPlusTree

Class TupleType

  • java.lang.Object
    • xxl.core.indexStructures.builder.BPlusTree.ManagedType
      • xxl.core.indexStructures.builder.BPlusTree.TupleType

  • public class TupleType
extends ManagedType
    Use this class if the index structure should use Tuple objects.

    Examples By the following a BPlusTree for using float objects is created. After data importing, a range query is executed. 
     TupleMetaData myTupleMetaData = new TupleMetaData("TupleTable", new ColumnMetaInfo[] {
 new ColumnMetaInfo(RelationalType.FLOAT, "FloatColumn")});
        
 BPlusTreeConfiguration requirements = new BPlusTreeConfiguration(new TupleType(myTupleMetaData));
 myTree = requirements.getBuilder().create();

 for(float i = 0; i < 100_000; i++) 
   myTree.insert(new ArrayTuple(i));
   
 Cursor c = myTree.rangeQuery(new ColumnComparableArrayTuple(20_000), new ColumnComparableArrayTuple(20_020));
 Cursors.println(c);
    See Also:
    Use primitive types like Integer or Float for an index structure, How to setup a BPlus tree easy and fast

      • TupleType

        public TupleType(ExtendedResultSetMetaData metaData)
          throws SQLException
        Specifies the tuple meta data managed by the index structure. Please note: Check that tuple meta data which should be inserted into the index structure and table meta data match.

        Example By the following a table called TupleTable is described. For further processing with e.g. BPlus tree a TupleType object is created. It contains methods which depend on the meta data and which are needed by the BPlus tree. 
         TupleMetaData myTupleMetaData = new TupleMetaData("TupleTable", new ColumnMetaInfo[] {
        new ColumnMetaInfo(RelationalType.INTEGER, "KEY_INTEGER"),
        new ColumnMetaInfo(RelationalType.INTEGER, "KEY_INTEGER"),
        new ColumnMetaInfo(RelationalType.VARCHAR, 50, "VARCHAR") });
 TupleType t = new TupleType(myTupleMetaData));
        Parameters:
        metaData - The table meta data
        Throws:
        SQLException

        public int[] getCompoundKeyIndices()
        Description copied from class: ManagedType
        Returns an array of indices which should be used as compounded key for indexing. Please node that this returns an integer array in which the first item is at position zero whereas the first column index for the table is one not zero.

        Caution: This methods should only be called if there is a way to compound a key through indices. For primitive types a call to this function will throw an Exception

      • setCompoundKey

        public void setCompoundKey(int[] compoundKeyIndices)
        Description copied from class: ManagedType
        Set the indices of the column which should be used as the compounded key for indexing (if possible, otherwise an Exception is thrown).

        The columns are compared lexicographically in descending order of their key indices given by compoundKeyIndices. The order of the table columns is the order in which you define it in compoundKeyIndices array. Thus, the first column (according to the first array item value) is compared with the first column of another tuple (according to the first array item value).

        If there is more than one key column, lets say two, the second columns are compared if there is equality in the first column for both tuples.

        Please mark that e.g. a compoundKeyIndices array [1,2] first compares the first column and after this (if necessary) the second column. Whereas [2,1] forces to compare at first the second column and after this (if necessary) the first column. Here, it must be ensured that the components of a tuple, which form a key, have to be comparable and also that there will be no duplicate values for a (compounded) key, so that a (compounded) key uniquely identifies a tuple.

        Specified by:
        setCompoundKey in class ManagedType
        Parameters:
        compoundKeyIndices - An array that contains the column indices. Please note that the order of the columns matters for comparing and that each column index is in bounds of the table column count.
        See Also:
        ManagedType.setCompoundKey(int[])
